<PROFILE>_AN-EFJCMAEFFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940610
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 94 / UK Company News: Johnson Matthey falls 11% - Shares lose 28p
as costs of Italian silver disposal hit results
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The cost of disposing of its Italian silver business helped to push 1993-94
profits down by 11 per cent at Johnson Matthey, the precious metals
technology group. The shares fell 28p to close at 558p.
Pre-tax profits were Pounds 65.4m on total turnover of Pounds 1.96bn for the
year to end March, compared with a previous Pounds 73.8m on turnover of
Pounds 1.85bn.
However, continuing activities showed operating profits rose by 15 per cent
to Pounds 81.6m (Pounds 70.8m) on turnover of Pounds 1.84bn (Pounds 1.76bn).
Mr David Davies, chairman and chief executive, said all four divisions had
shown higher profits. At the same time the group had embarked on several
joint ventures which would enable it to expand globally.
The group was moving from the cost cutting cycle of the past few years into
a cycle of growth, he said, citing the group's ceramics venture with
Cookson, planned autocatalyst plants in Malaysia and Mexico, and an
electronics venture with Mitsubishi in Japan.
The improvement at operating level was fuelled by the materials technology
division, which lifted profits from Pounds 20.8m to Pounds 28m. Mr Davies
said that biomedical products had continued to be a good profits earner, and
the electronic materials side had lifted profits in North America by 60 per
cent in sterling terms.
Profits at the automotive catalysts division rose from Pounds 27.1m to
Pounds 28.2m, with strong demand from North America offsetting a 15 per cent
decline in the European car market.
Precious metals profits edged ahead from Pounds 20.5m to Pounds 20.8m. A
rise in the price of platinum from Pounds 215 a troy ounce to Pounds 255 in
the period was offset by a further fall in the rhodium price, from Pounds
1,253 a troy ounce to Pounds 625.
The colour and print division improved profits from Pounds 11.3m to Pounds
13m.
Exceptional charges totalled Pounds 11.7m, compared with an exceptional gain
of Pounds 3.7m previously.
The book loss of Pounds 9m on the Italian sale, announced yesterday, was
offset by the disposal earlier in the year of the UK and Irish jewellery
businesses at a profit of Pounds 2.3m. A provision of Pounds 5m has been
charged for restructuring costs on Cookson Matthey Ceramics, the joint
venture with Cookson announced last March. and due to start on July 1.
Earnings per share were 23.7p, down from 27.1p. Earnings before exceptionals
were 27.6p. A final dividend of 8p is proposed, giving a total for the year
of 11.4p (10.3p).
COMMENT
The fall in the share price was surprising. Apart from the sale of the
Italian business, the results were in line with City expectations. Further
growth is expected. The group is investing a lot of money in the future.
Capital expenditure, at Pounds 65.4m, was more than twice the depreciation
charge, and research and development spending at Pounds 28.5m was also at a
record. It is taking its electronics expertise to Japan and its autocatalyst
expertise to east Asia and Mexico. By linking with Cookson, it is turning
the small colour and print division into a business big enough to compete on
global terms in the ceramics industry. Next year profits should be about
Pounds 90m, which gives a multiple of more than 17. This might look
expensive in the short term, but longer term the prospects are good.
</TEXT>
