FT  10 JUN 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
As they say on Radio 2, Friday Night Is Music Night. The programme of that
name offers middle-of-the-road popular music from the BBC Concert Orchestra
(7.30). There is a huge range of other music on offer elsewhere. Also at
7.30 Radio 3 begins its relay of the opening concert in the 1994 Aldeburgh
Festival with Britten's 'Sinfonia da Requiem', Stravinsky's 'The Flood', and
Mahler's 'Totenfeier'. If your taste is for more popular classical music the
Evening Concert on Classic FM at 8.00 provides Britten's 'Young Person's
Guide To The Orchestra', Arensky's 'Variations On A Theme Of Tchaikovsky',
and Rachmaninov's 'Rhapsody On A Theme Of Paganini'. At 10.00 John Peel
begins three hours of rock music from Tilburg, Holland, on Radio 1. If light
entertainment is your requirement from television on a Friday night, there
is a repeat of Red Dwarf, (9.00 BBC2) a situation comedy with an unusual
situation (deep space); the topical quiz show Have I Got News For You (10.00
BBC2); and Viva Cabaret on C4 which features some pretty appalling acts but
also Gayle Tuesday, a funny stand-up comedian (10.30).
