<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 94 / Doctors to fight performance pay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Two of the most powerful staff representative bodies in the health service
will meet next week to discuss a joint campaign against the introduction of
performance pay, the annual consultants' conference of the British Medical
Association was told yesterday.
Mr John Chawner, chairman of the BMA senior hospital doctors committee, said
the government's plans to introduce performance pay were 'so dangerous that
it is our duty to strongly resist them'.
Leaders of the BMA, which represents 80,000 doctors and surgeons, will join
leaders of the 300,000-strong Royal College of Nursing in opposing the
plans.
Mr Chawner said that there was mounting evidence that performance related
pay demotivated staff and disadvantaged women and ethnic minorities.
Simplistic incentive schemes would reward quantity rather than quality,
encouraging doctors to rush their work and neglect counselling, he said.
Mr Chawner also warned that allowing trusts to determine performance pay
would end national salary scales, since some would not be able to afford the
cost of bonuses.
This would undermine the work of the health service pay review bodies, which
would not know what doctors were earning. Nurses had as much to lose as
doctors, he added.
'They remember pay bargaining and the turmoil it caused to their profession
and the health service,' he said. 'This is why this government gave them
their own review body which is now threatened by the same government.'
However, the conference narrowly defeated a move to encourage consultants to
resign from the health service and offer freelance services.
</TEXT>
