<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 94 / Broadcast unions at the pain threshold: Rapid changes at the
BBC have left staff mistrustful of management
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY and ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
As strikes go, yesterday's second 24-hour stoppage at the BBC seemed
good-natured.
'Please don't break our strike,' said the senior radio journalist politely
to the few people making their way past the pickets through the heavy doors
of Broadcasting House in central London.
Yet the journalists and other broadcasting staff felt strongly enough about
management proposals to introduce performance pay and decentralised
negotiations on some aspects of terms and conditions that they left their
posts on the day of voting in the European elections and in five
by-elections - a day that could define the future of Mr John Major, the
prime minister.
The dispute - which is ostensibly about the nitty-gritty details of
performance pay and the exact nature of what can be negotiated at divisional
level - is fuelled by more than three years of rapid change and pain at the
BBC.
Last year 1,500 jobs were lost in the resource departments, which provide
everything from studios to editing. A further 700 will go this year, partly
a result of the move towards the target of having 25 per cent of BBC output
produced by independent companies.
Working relationships have been altered radically by Producer Choice, the
system that allows producers to buy in services from the open market.
It is a dispute marked by the staff's lack of trust in middle management.
Ironically Mr John Birt, the BBC director-general, appears sympathetic and
has said in public that his next task at the BBC is to do something about a
middle-management structure which he believes is too hierarchical and rigid.
Yet last night all the signs were that the two sides were digging in on
matters of principle, with senior management making it clear that
concessions offered in talks last week - such as accepting that everyone
will receive the negotiated standard pay increase each year - represented
the final offer.
Mr Bob Phillis, BBC deputy director-general, said last night: 'Unless we
have some element of pay which reflects performance, how on earth can we
retain, attract and reward high-quality staff?'
Mr Phillis said he would have preferred the management's final package -
offered after negotiations at Acas, the conciliation service, last week - to
have been put to union members in a ballot. The unions are taking action
under a strike ballot held on the management's original proposals.
Officials of the National Union of Journalists and Bectu, the main technical
union at the BBC, said yesterday that they had presented the BBC's revised
proposals honestly to their members at meetings.
Ms Christina Driver, national industrial officer at the BBC for Bectu, said
yesterday: 'We told the members we had not got what they wanted and no
significant gains had been made, but that there had been some movement. The
members were very strongly against acceptance of the offer.'
The union meetings - attended by about half the staff - rejected any
suggestion that the BBC offer should be put to a postal ballot because they
felt it would take too long and weaken momentum in the dispute.
Only about 40 per cent of members in either Bectu or the NUJ voted for
strike action in the initial postal ballots. Bectu members voted 61.3 per
cent in favour of stoppages. Support among NUJ members was 79.3 per cent.
The unions accept that the management did make some concessions in the four
days of talks at Acas to try to reassure staff about future conditions of
service, but they believe these did not go far enough to calm fears.
Ms Driver said: 'There is a crisis of morale among staff. It comes down to a
question of trust. They do not believe line managers will schedule their
work humanely without the protection of clear national agreements with the
unions.'
The unions want a national agreement on conditions of service to protect
working time and compensation payments for breaches of it.
BBC staff also oppose the corporation's plan to give line managers wider
discretion in deciding the implementation of performance pay for individuals
with no appeals procedure available, except for those facing possible pay
cuts.
The unions want every job to have an identifiable pay rate attached to it,
conditional on a 'fully competent' work performance. The new system would
also end annual increments for staff and national wage deals.
Ms Driver said: 'We believe this is a recipe for unfair and discriminatory
treatment. It will not deliver equal pay for work of equal value.'
The BBC believes its proposals will make the corporation more competitive so
it will be able to pay more competitive salaries as an integral part of the
modernising programme.
It is seen as ironic that industrial action taking programmes off the
screens is coming when the most painful period of change is over and when
the corporation is about to announce higher-than-expected savings of Pounds
125m this year - money that will be spent on programmes.
But as the top BBC management prepare today to take their case to staff
throughout the corporation, union feelings are running high. The NUJ says as
many as 600 BBC staff have joined or rejoined the union during the dispute.
</TEXT>
