<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 94 / Ofgas competition and tariffs director to return to DTI
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM LEWIS and DAVID LASCELLES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Greg McGregor, Ofgas director of competition and tariffs, is to leave the
gas industry regulator to take up a new post at the Department of Trade and
Industry.
His departure is seen by independent gas suppliers as a setback for plans by
the government and Ofgas to open up the domestic gas market.
'This is a real blow as Greg was one of the few people in Ofgas with
experience,' one executive from an independent gas company said.
Mr McGregor's move to the deregulation unit of the DTI follows a series of
difficulties encountered by Ms Clare Spottiswoode, Ofgas director-general.
Ms Spottiswoode was recently the target of a smear campaign which centred on
unfounded allegations about her private life and the closeness of her
working relationship with Mr John Michell, a senior DTI official.
Ofgas itself launched an unofficial probe in an attempt to find the source
of the stories but has not made any announcement.
Mr McGregor, employed by Ofgas for four years, was heavily involved in
writing the recently published joint DTI-Ofgas consultation document on the
introduction of competition in the domestic market.
As the director of competition and tariffs he played a central role for
Ofgas in its evidence to last year's Monopolies and Mergers Commission
investigation into the gas industry.
One gas consultant said yesterday: 'Mr McGregor and Clare never really saw
eye to eye.' He added that Mr McGregor had joined Ofgas at a time when Sir
James McKinnon, then director-general, was at the height of his difficulties
with British Gas.
One of Ms Spottiswoode's first decisions as director-general was to abolish
the post of deputy director-general. Mr McGregor's move leaves Ms
Spottiswoode and Ms Eileen Marshall, chief economics adviser, as the most
senior Ofgas staff.
Ofgas said yesterday that Mr McGregor had spent four years at Ofgas on
secondment from the DTI and that it was normal for him to be returning now.
'The DTI has a lot of work for him to do over there.'
No decision has been made on his replacement and Ms Marshall will take over
his duties meanwhile.
An Ofgas official said yesterday that the long-awaited consultation paper on
the rate of return British Gas will be allowed to earn from its
transportation assets would be released early next week. He added: 'At the
moment it is looking like it will be released on Monday. There are no
surprises or anything radical.'
</TEXT>
