<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 94 / Home Office accused of detention centre cover-up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EDWARD MORTIMER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Home Office was accused yesterday of covering up injuries sustained by
detainees during the riot at Campsfield House detention centre near Oxford
last Sunday night.
The Oxford-based Campaign to Close Campsfield said it had eyewitness and
film evidence to show that 'at least eight people' - all in Britain seeking
political asylum - were removed in four ambulances while an 'unknown number'
were removed in three more.
The Home Office has said only four people were injured.
The campaign also cited eyewitness accounts stating that 'a detainee jumped
head-first off the roof in protest, and that he had clearly sustained
serious injuries to his head'. Mr Bill MacKeith, president of Oxford Trade
Union Council, said the riot had been provoked by 'the removal, without
warning or justification' of an Algerian citizen for summary deportation the
next day from Gatwick.
After the riot, however, the government said the trouble had been stirred up
by demonstrators outside the fence.
On Monday Mr Charles Wardle, the junior Home Office minister, said the
student who had been deported had gone to Algeria voluntarily on September 2
but had then returned two months later using a forged passport.
</TEXT>
