<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 94 / US business investment 'to rise 8.9%'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US businesses plan to increase spending on plant and equipment by 8.9 per
cent in real terms this year after an 8.6 per cent increase last year, the
Commerce Department said yesterday.
The official survey of investment intentions supports anecdotal evidence
that US business confidence has risen to the point where many companies are
planning to build new plants or extend old facilities.
Since existing capacity is largely utilised, investment in new capacity is
widely seen as a prerequisite for continued non-inflationary growth.
Yesterday's survey follows reports of a slight weakening in retail spending
and home sales in recent weeks, partly as a result of increases in short and
long-term interest rates. However, it indicates only a marginal scaling back
of capital spending plans from earlier this year, suggesting that the
tighter monetary policy is not deterring productive investment
significantly.
Rather than losing momentum, the US recovery seems to be entering a more
mature phase in which business investment and exports take up the running
from personal consumption and housing.
The survey points to encouraging inflation trends in capital goods. The
average price of plant and equipment is expected to fall by 0.6 per cent
this year. The report shows across-the-board strength in capital spending,
with declines this year in only a few sectors.
The outlook is most buoyant in manufactured durable goods, where investment
is expected to rise 10.8 per cent in cash terms this year. The strongest
industries are blast furnaces and steelworks (up 37.5 per cent from 1993),
motor vehicles (up 28.3 per cent) and electrical machinery (up 12.1 per
cent). Figures for sectors are not adjusted for inflation.
Manufacturers of non-durable goods, by contrast, are planning to increase
capital spending by only 3.7 per cent from 1993. Relatively strong sectors
include rubber (up 9.3 per cent), chemicals (7.9 per cent) and textiles (7.4
per cent.) Investment in non-manufacturing is projected to rise 8.8 per cent
this year.
</TEXT>
