<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 94 / Irish health insurance move
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Private health insurance in Ireland will be opened up to competition but new
entrants will be prevented from 'cherry-picking' the low-risk sector of the
market, according to government proposals published this week. An EU
directive on non-life insurance comes into force next month, and the
proposals are intended to ensure Ireland's compliance with the directive in
the health insurance sector, by allowing other EU groups to enter the Irish
market. New entrants to the market would all have to offer a basic cover
package to all comers. Insurance companies would not be allowed to
discriminate against members opting for their schemes on the grounds of age,
sex, or health status. A non-profit making voluntary health insurance
scheme, the VHI, has operated alongside the public health service since
1957, and now has 1.3m members - over one third of the population.
</TEXT>
