<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 94 / Moscow reports denied
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
President Boris Yeltsin's spokesman yesterday described as a 'fabrication
and a lie' press reports that the Russian leader might sack prime minister
Victor Chernomyrdin, who is recovering from a kidney complaint.
Komsomolskaya Pravda newspaper yesterday quoted 'informed sources' as saying
that Mr Yeltsin wanted to replace him with Mr Yuri Skokov (pictured left), a
presidential crony with links to the defence industry and hardline Russian
politics. This is the latest report to surface in a time-honoured method of
spreading rumours to fight political battles in Russia - and may well
reflect genuine anger by the defence lobby at the government and lower
chamber of parliament's refusal to grant it extra spending in the 1994
budget. The reports have been aggravated by a military adviser to the
Russian prime minister who was quoted as saying that Mr Chernomyrdin might
resign if extra defence spending was pushed through by the upper chamber of
parliament and the defence lobby.
</TEXT>
