<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 94 / Record low Netherlands turnout in Euro-poll: UK
Conservatives fear disaster - Dutch Christian Democrats hope to gain lead
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Foreign Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Elections to the European Parliament began yesterday with a record low
turnout in the Netherlands and the ruling Conservative party in the UK
bracing itself for disaster.
In the Netherlands, traditionally one of the most pro-European electorates
in the EU, voter turnout slumped to 35 per cent, indicating that the
Christian Democrats of outgoing prime minister Mr Ruud Lubbers had recovered
the lead they lost in a general election last month.
Early exit polls in Denmark suggested no change in the overall balance
between pro- and anti-Europeans. Voting was stronger than expected, with a
turnout of 52 per cent compared with 46.2 per cent in 1989.
In Ireland, polling was slow through the day and a turnout of between 40 and
50 per cent of the country's 2.6m voters was expected. This would compare
with a 48 per cent turnout in the 1984 European election, and a 68 per cent
turnout in 1989, the latter coinciding with a general election.
Elections for the expanded 567-seat parliament will take place in the other
eight EU countries on Sunday. Official results are not due to be published
until Sunday night.
Preliminary forecasts by Dutch television showed that the Christian
Democrats stood to win 10 seats in the European Parliament, two seats ahead
of Labour, which is now the largest party in the national parliament.
For both the Christian Democrats and Labour, the results would be no
different from 1989, but would indicate a relative decline as the Dutch will
have six more seats in the parliament, for a total of 31.
The low Dutch turnout compared badly with the 47 per cent at the last
European election in 1989. Exit polls suggested D66, a left-of-centre party,
would win four seats - three more than it gained five years ago. The
Liberals seemed set to capture six seats, an increase of three. Direct
comparison between the 1989 and 1994 elections is complicated by the
expansion in the number of Dutch seats.
A low turnout traditionally helps the Christian Democrats and hurts Labour.
Another factor in favour of the Democrats may have been the appeal to voters
by Mr Lubbers, who is fighting an uphill battle to become president of the
European Commission.
In Denmark, the strongly pro-union Liberal Party, led by Mr Uffe
Ellemann-Jensen, the former foreign minister, stood to add one seat to win
four of Denmark's 16 seats, according to one exit poll.
Other polls indicated a strong performance by anti-European movements, the
People's Movement against the EU and the June Movement. However, the
anti-Europeans, although expected to increase their vote to about 25 per
cent from 18.9 per cent, were not expected to add to the four seats they
already hold.
The Social Democratic party, which dominates the present government
coalition, was expected to lose one of its four seats. Its share of the vote
appeared to have fallen to about 15 per cent from 23.3 per cent. Mr Poul
Nyrup Rasmussen, the prime minister, said it was 'a clearly disappointing
result'.
In the UK, polling was also slow in the election for 84 MEPs, increasing the
prospect that the Tories will lose up to two-thirds of their 32 seats, with
up to a dozen going to the Liberal Democrats and the rest to Labour.
However, Conservative managers believe that a late swing to the party could
allow it to hold up to 20 seats, which would be regarded by many activists
as a triumph for Mr John Major, the prime minister.
However, the latest opinion poll carried out by Mori for The Times indicated
that the party could be left with as few as four seats. The poll gave the
Conservatives just 23 per cent of the vote, compared with 51 per cent for
Labour and 20 per cent for the Liberal Democrats.
Such a result would expose Mr Major to renewed criticism from rightwing
Eurosceptic MPs, in spite of his generally Eurosceptic approach during the
campaign.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
