<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUN 94 / International Company News: Steven Green renews link with
Milken in Heron bid - Trusts belonging to the junk-bond king are among
partners bidding for Heron
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Eight years ago Mr Michael Milken, then the unquestioned junk-bond king,
backed a near-Dollars 200m deal which enabled Mr Steven Green to buy a
string of supermarkets in California.
Times have moved on. Last year, Mr Milken was released from jail after
serving a sentence for securities-related offences, and is battling prostate
cancer. Mr Green, meanwhile, has continued to add to a property empire built
up over the past 20 years.
This week, the connection was renewed. Mr Milken's family trusts (the
beneficiaries are his three children) are among the members of a limited
partnership put together by Mr Green to bid for Heron, the UK property
group.
'Mike Milken financed one of my real estate transactions. He had an
opportunity to see how we turned that investment into a very substantial
profit to the participants,' Mr Green said yesterday.
Until recently, Mr Green was little known outside US property circles. That
changed in 1990, when he was thrust into the limelight as chairman of E-II,
a holding company whose interests included the Samsonite luggage business,
Culligan International, a maker of water purifiers, and the 500 Fashion
group.
A protege of Mr Meshulam Riklis, the US deal-maker who had bought E-II from
American Brands in 1988, Mr Green was caught in the middle of a heated
battle for control of the company. Mr Riklis had been ousted in a bondholder
revolt.
Investors led by Mr Carl Icahn, the financier who at one time owned TWA,
later rejected Mr Green's plans for restructuring the debt-laden company and
forced it into bankruptcy protection.
In the following years, Mr Icahn and Mr Leon Black, supporter of Mr Green
and a former head of mergers and acquisitions at Drexel Burnham Lambert,
fought for control of E-II, before Mr Black finally held sway a year ago.
Now renamed Astrum International, the holding company has emerged from
bankruptcy protection, with Mr Green still at the helm. He has in the
meantime been growing his US property vehicle, Auburndale Properties.
This now owns more than 11m sq ft of residential and industrial property in
the US. With the bid for Heron, Mr Green hopes to launch himself for the
first time in the European property markets.
</TEXT>
