<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUN 94 / International Company News: Accounting rules for US options
delayed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US accounting rules for stock options granted to executives are being
delayed to consider the issues raised.
The rules, the first part of which was intended to have been introduced at
the end of this year, have provoked a fierce reaction from companies in the
US, particularly smaller ones.
Under a draft issued for comment last summer, the Financial Accounting
Standards Board proposed that companies should disclose more information
about the value of stock options granted to executives, and the cost of the
options to the company should be taken as an expense against profits.
The proposals have angered many fast-growing smaller companies. Unable to
match the salaries and cash bonuses paid by large companies, these companies
seek to attract talented executives by issuing options which give the holder
the opportunity to make big capital gains. If taken as an expense, these
would add substantially to the reported costs of many US companies.
Mr Dennis Berisford, chairman of FASB, said yesterday: 'All the provisions
of the exposure draft, including expense recognition and measurement, will
be reconsidered by the board.'
However, Ms Diana Willis, project manager at FASB for the stock option
rules, said this did not imply that the board was backtracking on the
proposals.
The board always reconsidered all rules after receiving comments from
interested parties, she said.
FASB said it was delaying the first stage of the rules, which would have
required additional disclosure relating to stock options in companies' 1994
financial statements.
The reconsideration of the draft rules is 'not expected to be completed
before the first quarter of 1995', it added. FASB had hoped to publish final
rules by the end of this year.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
