<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUN 94 / Tories claim late surge of support ahead of Euro poll: Lib
Dem by-election candidate's defection boosts Labour hopes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Conservatives last night claimed a strong late surge in support as Mr
John Major prepared for the most daunting test of his government's authority
since the 1992 general election.
But a spectacular defection by a Liberal Democrat by-election candidate
boosted Labour's confidence that the European elections will provide its
strongest performance in a nationwide poll since 1966.
Optimism among ministers that Tory losses could be limited to perhaps a
dozen of their 32 seats was dented by a new opinion poll suggesting it will
win a smaller share of the vote than in any other postwar election.
The government has already discounted a crushing defeat at the hand of the
Liberal Democrats in the once safe Tory seat of Eastleigh in today's clutch
of five by-elections.
Mr Major used the final day of campaigning to emphasise the Conservatives'
claim to be the only party willing to stand up for Britain's interests in
Europe.
Seizing on the latest indicators as evidence that the pace of economic
recovery was accelerating, the prime minister said the campaign had provided
a powerful endorsement of its call for a flexible rather than centralised
European Union. Britain was leading Europe out of recession.
Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign secretary, ended an intensive nationwide tour
with a similarly confident assertion that the government had recaptured core
Conservative supporters.
The Liberal Democrats were stunned by the public announcement from Mr Alec
Kellaway, the party's candidate in the Newham North East by-election, that
he intends to join the Labour party.
With Mr Tony Blair widely expected to win the leadership election which will
follow immediately today's poll, it was being cited by Labour as evidence
that Labour is poised to regain its lost following in southern England.
The two opposition parties wound up their campaigns by insisting the outcome
would represent voters' judgment on Mr Major's 'failed' government.
Labour officials were predicting privately that the party is assured of
around 55 of the 84 seats being contested in Britain. The Liberal Democrats,
currently unrepresented in the Strasbourg assembly, are confident of
securing at least three and hopeful of winning up to 10.
A Mori opinion poll in today's Times, based on an unusually large sample,
supported opposition hopes that the electorate is ready to punish the
government for its domestic record.
The poll gave Labour a 28 point lead, with 51 per cent of the projected
vote, against the Conservatives' 23 per cent and the Liberal Democrats' 20
per cent. Mori calculated that on the basis of those figures the number of
Conservative seats in Strasbourg could fall to between four and 15.
Lib Dem candidate rocks party, Page 10
Editorial Comment, Page 23
</TEXT>
