<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUN 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It would be an insult to most reporters to describe their programmes as a
'meander' around their subjects, yet it seems quite reasonable and not the
least damaging when it is Wooldridge On Whisky. Wooldridge is so laid back
and such a natural raconteur that virtually any subject he covers is sure to
be entertaining without any of that straining for drama which you usually
get on television. Sure enough, the opening episode was funny and seemingly
effortless; invariably the mark of hard work (8.00 BBC2). At 9.30 Channel 4
repeats the remarkable interview with the late Dennis Potter first shown on
Without Walls in April. At that point Potter was staying alive on vitamins,
cigarettes, and the liquid morphine which he swigged from a flask as he
talked to Melvyn Bragg. I suspect that you get the truth about Potter's
beliefs from his dramas, but this interview reveals as much about Potter the
man as any programme ever achieved. The colour film shot by George Stevens
as he advanced from Normandy to Berlin in 1944/45 provides a unique record
which BBC2 repeats in D-Day To Berlin (9.45).
</TEXT>
