<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUN 94 / Output betters market hopes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Manufacturing output grew by an unexpectedly strong 1.1 per cent in April,
indicating that the economic recovery is still robust, in spite of the
impact of tax rises.
Industrial production, which includes the more volatile oil and gas sector,
was 1.6 per cent higher on the month, according to the Central Statistical
Office. Both figures, which are seasonally adjusted, were well ahead of
market expectations of month-on-month increases of about 0.5 per cent.
However, analysts said that the rise partly reflected a rebound from March,
when both production and output fell. Those declines were revised to 0.6 per
cent and 0.7 per cent yesterday.
Monthly figures are volatile and the CSO prefers to concentrate on
three-monthly averages. These show that manufacturing output was 1.2 per
cent higher in the three months to April than in the previous three months,
while industrial production was 1 per cent ahead. If the three months to
April are compared with the same three months in 1993, manufacturing output
has risen 2.3 per cent, while industrial production is up 4.4 per cent.
In spite of last month's growth, manufacturing output is still about 3.7 per
cent below the its pre-recession levels. Recent revisions to the trade
figures mean that manufacturing output in 1993 is now believed to have been
0.1 per cent lower than previously estimated.
Industrial production is just 0.4 per cent below its peak, reached in June
1990. Its strength is mainly due to oil and gas output, which in April
passed its previous record level set in May 1987. Oil and gas output in the
three months to April was 37.2 per cent higher than in the same period a
year ago. Electricity, gas and water supply output rose 5.9 per cent between
March and April because of colder-than-average temperatures. However, coal
production continued to decline.
Manufacturing output was boosted by a 14.8 per cent surge in coke and
nuclear fuels production, which rebounded after maintenance work in February
and March.
</TEXT>
